// @test regression/eq-operator-type-mismatch
// @description `==`/`!=` type mismatches render as TV's CE10123, not our old "cannot apply" wording. When one operand is a LITERAL, TV anchors the error at the literal (the offender) and reports the OTHER operand's type as expected, independent of left/right order: `cb == 1` and `close == "x"` flag the literal as expr1; `"x" == close` flags the left literal as expr0. The bool side renders with its real qualifier (const/series/input bool). Probed 2026-06-25 via pine-lint --tv, see #57 / INV096.
// @expects parse: success
// @expects error: line=4, message=/Cannot call "operator ==" with argument "expr1"="1".*"literal int".*"const bool"/
// @expects error: line=5, message=/Cannot call "operator ==" with argument "expr1"="hi".*"literal string".*"const bool"/
// @expects error: line=7, message=/Cannot call "operator ==" with argument "expr1"="1".*"literal int".*"series bool"/
// @expects error: line=9, message=/Cannot call "operator !=" with argument "expr1"="2".*"literal int".*"input bool"/
// @expects error: line=10, message=/Cannot call "operator ==" with argument "expr1"="x".*"literal string".*"series float"/
// @expects error: line=11, message=/Cannot call "operator ==" with argument "expr0"="x".*"literal string".*"series float"/
// @expects errors: 6

//@version=6
indicator("eq-operator-type-mismatch")
bool cb = true
e1 = cb == 1
e2 = cb == "hi"
series bool sb = close > open
e3 = sb == 1
ib = input.bool(true)
e4 = ib != 2
e5 = close == "x"
e6 = "x" == close
okFloat = close == 2
okInt = 5 == 5
plot(okFloat ? 1 : okInt ? 2 : 0)
